            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marcus Turner is the quiet foundation upon which a small piece of San Francisco\u2019s glittering innovation rests. Born and raised in the Fillmore District, his childhood was scored by the sounds of jazz from the street and his father\u2019s tools in the garage. His dad, a master mechanic, and his mom, a city clerical worker, instilled in Marcus a powerful work ethic and a practical, hands-on approach to life. While school bored him, he could strip down and rebuild a small engine by age fifteen. He earned his diploma and, seeing the financial strain on his family, immediately entered the workforce.\n\nHis career began not with a degree, but with a tool belt. In the late 1990s, he landed a job on the maintenance crew for a biotech startup in Mission Bay. It was a world away from his own, filled with PhDs and ambitious entrepreneurs. But Marcus found his niche. While others chased venture capital, he mastered the building\u2019s complex HVAC systems, its sensitive electrical grids, and its intricate plumbing. He became the company\u2019s institutional memory, the one person who knew why a wall was where it was or how to coax the aging backup generator to life during a critical power outage. His quiet competence and unflappable reliability saw him promoted from crew to supervisor, and eventually to Facilities Manager.\n\nNow, at 46, Marcus lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Outer Richmond. His daily routine is a bedrock of consistency. He catches the N Judah Muni line before dawn, the 5.8-mile ride a quiet time for him to listen to a sports podcast before the day\u2019s chaos begins. At the sleek research campus, he manages a small team, coordinates with vendors, and solves problems the scientists never even know they have.\n\nA lifelong bachelor, his closest relationship is with his younger sister and her kids in Oakland, whose college funds he quietly contributes to. His social life consists of a weekly poker night with old friends and catching Warriors games at a local bar. Marcus has watched his city transform, the working-class neighborhoods of his youth now landscapes of glass condos. His dream isn\u2019t extravagant; it\u2019s to save enough to buy a small condo, a tangible piece of the city he has served his entire life. He is a testament to an older San Francisco\u2014built not on code, but on competence and character."
