            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the smell of grease and his father\u2019s quiet nod. He was fifteen, knuckles raw, having finally reassembled a faulty carburetor. School had been a blur of failing grades, but in the Fillmore garage, he\u2019d made something broken whole again. His dad clapped him on the shoulder, a rare, solid gesture of approval that felt more real than any diploma. In that moment, Marcus understood his worth wasn't in books, but in the steady, honest work of his hands. It was a language he was born to speak.\n\n2.\nThe massive storm hit around 2001, and the building went dark. Panic flickered in the eyes of the PhDs, their million-dollar cell cultures dying without power. Marcus, then in his mid-20s, felt a surge of pure focus. He navigated the blacked-out basement by memory, coaxing the ancient generator to life with a specific sequence of switches he alone knew. As the lab lights hummed back on, no one threw a parade, but he felt their silent respect. He wasn't one of them, but he kept their world turning.\n\n3.\nAround 2012, he walked past his old block in the Fillmore. The corner liquor store where he\u2019d bought baseball cards was gone, replaced by a minimalist cafe with a single orchid in the window. He saw the prices and felt a hollow ache. It wasn't just a building that had vanished; it was a piece of his history, erased and written over in a language he couldn\u2019t afford. That day, the vague desire to own something here hardened into a necessary, stubborn goal against the changing tide.\n\n4.\nAt a family barbecue in his sister\u2019s Oakland backyard a few years ago, he slipped her an envelope. \u201cFor Maya\u2019s college fund,\u201d he mumbled, deflecting her thanks. Later, he watched his niece laugh, chasing a soccer ball, and felt a profound, quiet satisfaction. His pre-dawn Muni rides, the leaky pipes, the endless schematics\u2014they all translated into this one, perfect moment of her future. This was the foundation he was building. It was the best investment he\u2019d ever made, and it had nothing to do with stocks.\n\n5.\nJust last week, riding the N Judah through the pre-dawn fog, he watched the city lights blur past. The train car was filled with other early risers\u2014nurses, baristas, custodians. He felt an unspoken kinship with them, the people who oiled the gears of the city. While the newest residents paid fortunes to see the view, he was part of the machinery that made it run. In the familiar rumble of the train, he felt a quiet ownership, a sense of belonging that no property deed could yet grant him."
